7
00:00:42,250 --> 00:00:43,500
Story of the Week.

8
00:00:43,500 --> 00:00:49,075
Sora Is Dead — And That Says Everything About OpenAI in 2026.

9
00:00:49,075 --> 00:01:02,575
On a single Tuesday in the last week of March, OpenAI axed the Sora video app, dissolved the billion-dollar Disney deal, reassigned a manager — and simultaneously announced a fresh $10B funding tranche .

10
00:01:02,575 --> 00:01:12,387
The message was clearer than any press release: when you have $120B in investor capital behind you , you need to deliver, not experiment.

11
00:01:12,387 --> 00:01:16,050
Sora had a structural problem after its spectacular launch.

12
00:01:16,050 --> 00:01:25,337
Runway, Pika, and Chinese competitor Kling caught up significantly within months and were considered competitive with OpenAI's solution in many respects .

13
00:01:25,337 --> 00:01:30,337
Internally, the app was deemed not competitive enough for a standalone market presence.

14
00:01:30,337 --> 00:01:41,937
Rather than continuing to invest, the leadership team decided to redirect resources toward enterprise products and B2B revenue — the only viable course ahead of a potential IPO.

15
00:01:41,937 --> 00:01:46,687
The numbers are stark: A Disney deal worth $1B was dissolved .

16
00:01:46,687 --> 00:01:57,162
SoftBank is financing its $30B share in OpenAI's round through a 12-month, unsecured loan of $40B from JPMorgan and Goldman Sachs .

17
00:01:57,162 --> 00:02:09,587
Private equity investors receive a guaranteed minimum return of 17.5%  — unusual for a startup and a strong signal that analysts interpret as preparation for an imminent public offering.

18
00:02:09,587 --> 00:02:15,762
For developers and users, this means: The OpenAI portfolio is shrinking strategically.

19
00:02:15,762 --> 00:02:27,362
Anyone who bet on Sora integration needs to replan — Runway Gen-3, Pika 2.0, and Kling are mature alternatives without OpenAI's valuation pressure.

20
00:02:27,362 --> 00:02:35,525
For enterprise customers, the pivot signals that OpenAI is focusing more heavily on API products and B2B offerings.

21
00:02:35,525 --> 00:02:40,737
Open questions: The decision raises questions about the "how," not the "what."

22
00:02:40,737 --> 00:02:45,862
External developers who had built on the Sora API learned about its end from the press .

23
00:02:45,862 --> 00:02:52,462
That's not a good sign for platform trust in a pre-IPO year when OpenAI is counting on enterprise credibility.

24
00:02:52,462 --> 00:03:07,975
Bottom line: OpenAI is cleaning house — not because Sora was bad, but because $120B in investor capital demands a different focus than a consumer video experiment that China can copy faster than OpenAI can scale.

25
00:03:07,975 --> 00:03:09,312
More Top Stories.

26
00:03:09,312 --> 00:03:15,175
Anthropic vs. Pentagon: Federal Court Sets Precedent for AI and Free Speech.

27
00:03:15,175 --> 00:03:20,337
A federal judge has preliminarily lifted the Pentagon's blacklisting of Anthropic .

28
00:03:20,337 --> 00:03:31,212
The DoD had classified Anthropic as a "supply chain risk" — citing security concerns around Anthropic's major investors (including Google, Amazon, and Saudi PIF).

29
00:03:31,212 --> 00:03:43,725
The court, however, also saw potential retaliation against the company's critical press coverage of the DoD procurement process and deemed the classification a potential violation of the First Amendment .

30
00:03:43,725 --> 00:03:48,362
The case was confirmed by TechCrunch, CNBC, and WSJ .

31
00:03:48,362 --> 00:03:57,562
The ruling is historic: it is the first time an AI organization has successfully won a First Amendment lawsuit against a US federal agency.

32
00:03:57,562 --> 00:04:05,825
The blacklisting would have effectively excluded Anthropic from the government procurement market — one of the highest-volume AI markets globally .

33
00:04:05,825 --> 00:04:15,512
Bloomberg also reports that Anthropic is weighing an IPO as early as October 2026  — the company is visibly fighting from a position of strength.

34
00:04:15,512 --> 00:04:16,337
So what?

35
00:04:16,337 --> 00:04:26,287
For the entire AI industry, this is a relevant signal: regulatory arbitrariness through government classifications now has a proven legal counterweight.

36
00:04:26,287 --> 00:04:32,087
Future administrations will think twice before restricting AI companies for political reasons.

37
00:04:32,087 --> 00:04:38,162
iOS 27 Opens Siri to Claude, Gemini & Co. — Apple's Quiet Revolution

38
00:04:39,087 --> 00:04:48,112
According to Bloomberg reporter Mark Gurman , iOS 27 will bring a new extensions system allowing third-party chatbots as a Siri backend.

39
00:04:48,112 --> 00:04:57,587
Users will be able to set Claude, Gemini, or other AI assistants as the default intelligence for Siri requests — analogous to choosing a default browser .

40
00:04:57,587 --> 00:05:03,500
Apple plans to announce at WWDC; launch is scheduled for fall 2026.

41
00:05:03,500 --> 00:05:14,375
The strategic dimension is significant: Apple is opening access to approximately one billion active devices  to Anthropic, Google, and potential additional providers.

42
00:05:14,375 --> 00:05:21,037
The backdrop includes both competitive pressure and regulatory requirements under the EU Digital Markets Act.

43
00:05:21,037 --> 00:05:28,475
For Anthropic, this represents a direct distribution channel that would otherwise require years of independent app development.

44
00:05:28,475 --> 00:05:29,300
So what?

45
00:05:29,300 --> 00:05:33,775
Apple loses little — Siri was never a differentiator against Android.

46
00:05:33,775 --> 00:05:42,112
The AI assistant market gains a distribution surface that could fundamentally break up the duopoly between ChatGPT and Google Assistant.

47
00:05:42,112 --> 00:05:45,512
Whoever builds the better API experience wins.

48
