00:07:59,812 --> 00:08:00,962
Fail of the Week.

69
00:08:00,962 --> 00:08:04,800
"We're Building Our Own Model" — Cursor's Kimi Surprise

70
00:08:04,800 --> 00:08:16,137
Cursor presented "Composer 2" as an in-house AI coding model — and forgot to mention that it is built on Kimi 2.5 from Moonshot AI, an Alibaba-backed Chinese company .

71
00:08:16,137 --> 00:08:22,512
This wasn't discovered through an audit, but by an X user named Fynn who found code hints and made them public.

72
00:08:22,512 --> 00:08:24,512
Cursor subsequently confirmed.

73
00:08:24,512 --> 00:08:29,037
Root Cause: Not a technical bug — a deliberate communication failure.

74
00:08:29,037 --> 00:08:32,725
Cursor chose not to proactively disclose the model's origin.

75
00:08:32,725 --> 00:08:42,300
In the geopolitical climate of 2026, where Chinese AI models are a sensitive topic, this was a calculated non-disclosure that has come back to bite them .

76
00:08:42,300 --> 00:08:51,262
What we learn: Anyone building an AI product must disclose the model's origin — especially when the base model raises geopolitical questions.

77
00:08:51,262 --> 00:09:00,087
"Nobody asked" is not an acceptable communication strategy in 2026 for a highly valued tool with a broad developer user base.

78
